Step 3: Spring Boot receives the request

The first thing Spring MVC does is

Incoming Request
      │
      ▼
DispatcherServlet

Before calling your controller,

Spring checks

Are there any Interceptors?

Yes.

You registered one.

RequestInterceptor
Step 4: How was it registered?

Your original configuration

@Override
public void addInterceptors(InterceptorRegistry registry) {
    registry.addInterceptor(requestInterceptor);
}

means

Apply this interceptor to EVERY SINGLE REQUEST

So

/connections/users

✔

/connections/posts

✔

/connections/swagger-ui

✔

/connections/v3/api-docs

✔

Everything

Spring never differentiates between Swagger and business APIs.

Step 5: Request enters RequestInterceptor

Your code

String userId = request.getHeader("X-User-Id");

Browser never sent

X-User-Id

So

userId = null

Then

Long.valueOf(userId);

becomes

Long.valueOf(null);

Java internally tries

Parse "null" into Long

Impossible.

So Java throws

NumberFormatException

whose message is

Cannot parse null string

Exactly the error you saw.

Why did Swagger fail before even opening?

Many people think

Browser
      │
Swagger UI

No.

Actually

Browser
      │
      ▼
RequestInterceptor
      │
      ▼
Swagger Controller

Your interceptor executes before Swagger.

Since the interceptor throws an exception,

Swagger never gets a chance to execute.

Visual Flow
Browser
      │
      ▼
DispatcherServlet
      │
      ▼
RequestInterceptor
      │
Long.valueOf(null)
      │
Exception
      │
Response
{
   "Cannot parse null string"
}

Swagger controller is never reached.

Why did changing WebMvcConfigurer fix it?

Original

registry.addInterceptor(requestInterceptor);

means

Apply interceptor on

Everything.

New configuration

registry.addInterceptor(requestInterceptor)
        .excludePathPatterns(
                "/swagger-ui/**",
                "/swagger-ui.html",
                "/v3/api-docs/**"
        );

Now Spring internally stores

Interceptor

Apply to

ALL URLs

EXCEPT

/swagger-ui/**
/swagger-ui.html
/v3/api-docs/**

Now suppose the request is

/connections/swagger-ui/index.html

Spring checks

Does it match

/swagger-ui/**

?

Yes.

Therefore

Skip RequestInterceptor.

Flow becomes

Browser
      │
      ▼
DispatcherServlet
      │
      ▼
Swagger Controller
      │
Swagger UI

No exception.

What about business APIs?

Suppose request is

/connections/request/15

Spring checks

Does it match

/swagger-ui/**

No

/v3/api-docs/**

No

Then

Run RequestInterceptor.

Now flow is

Browser
     │
     ▼
Gateway
     │
Adds X-User-Id
     │
Connections Service
     │
RequestInterceptor
     │
Reads X-User-Id
     │
Controller

Everything works.

Why did we also change RequestInterceptor?

Your old code

String userId = request.getHeader("X-User-Id");

AuthContextHolder.setCurrentUserId(Long.valueOf(userId));

assumes

"The header will always be present."

That assumption isn't always true.

A request could reach the service:

without the Gateway,
from Postman,
from another microservice,
due to a configuration mistake.

In those cases,

Long.valueOf(null)

would crash the application.

So we changed it to

if (userId == null || userId.isBlank()) {
    response.setStatus(401);
    return false;
}

Now instead of crashing,

the interceptor returns a proper response:

401 Unauthorized

This is much better than an unexpected

500 Internal Server Error

because the client immediately knows the request is missing authentication information.

Why use both excludePathPatterns() and the null check?

They solve different problems.

excludePathPatterns(...)

Controls which URLs should bypass the interceptor.

Swagger
↓

Don't execute interceptor.
Null check inside the interceptor

Protects all other requests from invalid or missing headers.

Business API
↓

Header missing

↓

Return 401

↓
Don't crash.


